them — there are many; do not miss any. (After conversion, `grep -c \"func test\"` should be 0 and `grep -c \"@Test\"` should equal the original test count.)\n4. Assertions (split on the TOP-LEVEL comma, respecting nested ()/[]/{}/<> and string literals — many assertions here have arrays/Sets/dictionaries with internal commas):\n   - `XCTAssertEqual(a, b)` → `#expect(a == b)` (trailing message string → 2nd arg of #expect)\n   - `XCTAssertNotEqual(a, b)` → `#expect(a != b)`\n   - `XCTAssertNil(x)` → `#expect(x == nil)` ; `XCTAssertNotNil(x)` → `#expect(x != nil)`\n   - `XCTAssertTrue(x)` → `#expect(x)` ; `XCTAssertFalse(x)` → `#expect(!(x))`\n   - `XCTAssertGreaterThan`→`>`, `…GreaterThanOrEqual`→`>=`, `…LessThan`→`<`, `…LessThanOrEqual`→`<=`\n   - `XCTAssert(cond)` → `#expect(cond)`\n   - `XCTFail(\"msg\")` → `Issue.record(\"msg\")`\n   - When the LHS of an equality uses `??` or other low-precedence operators, parenthesize it: `#expect((a ?? []) == b)`.\n5. Keep ALL helper methods (e.g. `makeMovie`, `makePeople`, any `private func`), nested types/enums, comments, and `// MARK:` section headers EXACTLY.\n\nWork through the file in order so nothing is skipped. After finishing: verify with grep that there are zero `XCTAssert`/`XCTFail`/`XCTestCase`/`import XCTest`/`func test` occurrences, the suite is `@Suite @MainActor struct`, and the count of `@Test` equals the original number of test methods. Do NOT build (siblings still mid-migration). Report: original test count vs `@Test` count, and confirm zero XCTest references remain."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1751,"cache_read_input_tokens":761183,"output_tokens":5027,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1751,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tok